{"title": "Stock Sh\u014dnen Rival", "content": "If your series has a Stock Sh\u014dnen Hero, he's going to need a recurring opponent. Enter the Stock Sh\u014dnen Rival.\n\nThis character is usually the Privileged Rival, The Lancer (a rival who is also your teammate can make for good stories, hence why Fighting the Lancer is a thing), or even an enemy. Unlike the optimistic Stock Shonen Hero, who believes in The Power of Friendship and easily amasses True Companions, the cynical Rival will believe in the power of his own strength. In terms of intelligence, the Stock Shonen Hero will (often) be a Kindhearted Simpleton (heavy emphasis on \"simpleton\") while the Stock Shonen Rival will have more knowledge about the Serious Business at hand (although often this knowledge came at the price of Sacrificed Basic Skill for Awesome Training). In terms of power levels, the rival usually starts off stronger than the hero. As the hero grows stronger and slowly closes the gap, the rival may become openly adversarial or even pull a Heel\u0096Face Turn, fearing that his worldview is being challenged by this nobody. Alternatively, he may believe the dark side will increase his power which often leads to a one-on-one fight between the two. Often, the Hero's optimism and strong sense of justice will make the Rival question his own reasons for fighting, which may trigger their own Character Development arc.\n\nThere's a great chance that the Hero will triumph over the Rival in ideals if not in power. In keeping with the shonen Coming-of-Age Story about making friends and overcoming obstacles through sheer willpower, the Rival represents something contrary to these messages that the Hero must overcome for the story to hit home.\n\nAn encompassing trope that's usually some combination of an Anti-Hero, Arrogant Kung-Fu Guy, Instant Expert, Jerkass \u2014> Jerk with a Heart of Gold, Blood Knight, Heel\u0096Face Revolving Door, Inferiority Superiority Complex, Reformed, but Not Tamed, Revenge, Byronic Hero, Grumpy Bear, Perpetual Frowner with the occasionally Smirk, and Evil Sounds Deep. In some cases he may also be a Char Clone. He also tends to be a Chick Magnet and Mr. Fanservice. It may also include visual tropes such as a Blue Is Heroic (Sort of), Evil Wears Black, Tall, Dark, and Handsome, or Red and Black and Evil All Over. He tends to have ice, fire, or lightning powers and more often tends to wield a blade of some sort. His dynamic with the hero tends to be the the blue to the Hero's red, Shadow Archetype.", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/StockShonenRival", "media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/Bakugan", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/Bakugan", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/BakuganBattlePlanet", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/Beyblade", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/BakutenShootBeyblade", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/MetalFightBeyblade", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/Bleach", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/CardcaptorSakura", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/DragonBall", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/FairyTail", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/Haikyuu", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/HunterXHunter", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/MyHeroAcademia", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/Naruto", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/Pokemon", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/PokemonGoldAndSilver", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/PokemonAdventures", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/PokemonGoldenBoys", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/PokemonGoldAndSilver", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/ShamanKing", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/RanmaOneHalf", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/YuGiOh", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/YukiYunaIsAHero", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/YuYuHakusho", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/BlackClover", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/NeonGenesisEvangelion", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/TengenToppaGurrenLagann", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/PuellaMagiMadokaMagica", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/PuellaMagiMadokaMagicaTheMovieRebellion", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/PuellaMagiMadokaMagicaTheMovieRebellion", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/OnePu